## Sensitive Skin: Why It Happens and What to Do About It

Sensitive skin is not a separate skin type and not a diagnosis. In most cases, it is a condition in which the skin begins to react strongly to factors that previously caused no discomfort. Redness, burning, tightness, or a general feeling of irritation can appear even with familiar skincare routines or without an obvious trigger. 🫧
It is important to understand that sensitivity is a signal. This is how the skin communicates that its balance and protective mechanisms have been disrupted. 🤍

## What sensitive skin really is

The skin performs a protective function: it helps retain moisture and shields the body from external influences. When this barrier weakens, the skin becomes more vulnerable to irritants.
Sensitivity may present as:
• burning or stinging sensations;
• redness;
• tightness;
• reactions to water, cosmetics, or temperature changes.

At the same time, the skin may look normal or show only minimal visible changes. ⚖️

[IMAGE: articles/24_sensitive_skin_causes_and_care/portrait-of-a-young-woman-with-skin-texture-with-r-2026-01-11-11-01-16-utc.webp | Sensitive skin can react with redness, breakouts, and uneven texture even to common everyday triggers.]

## Why skin becomes sensitive

Skin sensitivity usually has multiple causes that often overlap.
The most common factors include:
• a weakened skin barrier;
• frequent changes or overuse of active skincare products;
• stress and chronic tension 😮‍💨
• sudden changes in temperature or climate;
• poor sleep and impaired recovery 😴
• nutrition and deficiencies in essential nutrients.

Even skin that was previously resilient can become sensitive over time under these conditions.

## The role of the skin barrier

The skin barrier is the foundation of skin resilience. When it functions properly, the skin remains calm and stable. When it is compromised, moisture loss increases and irritants penetrate more easily.
As a result, the skin:
• becomes red more quickly;
• reacts more strongly to skincare products;
• recovers more slowly;
• loses its sense of comfort.

Supporting the skin barrier is a key element in managing sensitivity. 💧
Sensitivity and lifestyle
Skin condition is closely connected to overall health. Lack of sleep, stress, and an irregular routine directly affect skin reactivity.
The impact is especially noticeable with:
• chronic stress;
• insufficient sleep;
• fatigue;
• unbalanced nutrition.

Under these circumstances, the skin becomes depleted more quickly and adapts poorly to external stressors. 🌿

## What really helps with sensitive skin

Managing sensitivity does not start with finding a “perfect” product, but with simplification and consistency.
In practice, this means:
• reducing the number of skincare products used;
• avoiding frequent experiments with new products;
• gentle cleansing without aggressive ingredients;
• regular hydration and barrier support;
• paying attention to sleep quality and stress levels. ✨

The calmer and more consistent the approach, the faster the skin regains balance and comfort.

## Conclusion

Sensitive skin is not a problem on its own, but a response to internal and external overload. Understanding the causes of sensitivity allows for a gentle and mindful approach that does not worsen irritation. Supporting the skin barrier, simplifying skincare, and paying attention to lifestyle factors help the skin gradually restore resilience and comfort. 🤍

